ilosophy of sadh=\r\nana and specially Tantrik sadhana, is to create a formation of the deity us=\r\ning ones own prana-shakti through the aid of repeated rituals and procedure=\r\ns and mantras etc. If you think carefully, you will realize that every idol=\r\n, ever homa agni needs a pranapratisthapana ritual before starting. The sad=\r\nhaka used the force of his/her own\n pranashakti to infuse life into a subtl=\r\ne formation of the deity. Once this process is successfully done, this subl=\r\nte formation of the deity which exists in the subtle plane, has a life of i=\r\nts own. It can then guide the sadhaka through the path and eventually, one =\r\nday lead him/her to the real abode of the deity which is the karana-jagat (=\r\nbeyond this astral plane). If a person is able to awaken his/her Kundalini =\r\nshakti, and make it identify/create such an astral formation of the deity, =\r\nit becomes an even more powerful force. It is, from our limited human persp=\r\nective, as much a powerful entity as we may imagine, yet it is often not th=\r\ne actual Deity yet. Exactly the same thing has been described by Sri Vimala=\r\nnanda in the Aghora books, if you read carefully.&nbsp; &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;When a sadh=\r\naka has been able to associate with such an astral formation of the deity, =\r\nit can guide the sadhaka along the path provided the sadhaka also is trying=\r\n to work hard and sincerely\n to reach the causal planes (the real spiritual=\r\n planes of existence where the real force of the Deity originates). The dif=\r\nference, if you ask, between this astral formation of the deity and the rea=\r\nl deity is that, the former is neither bound nor capable by itself of causi=\r\nng a complete and total transformation of the average human nature without =\r\na proactive help of the sadhaka. Whereas, if one reaches the plane of the G=\r\nreat Gods, which is where the real deity exists, one cannot avoid being tra=\r\nnsformed in mind, emotions, body etc. And what kind of a transformation wil=\r\nl it be? One that will reflect to the world as a greater and genuine humili=\r\nty, sense of deep surrender to the Divine at ALL time and unfailingly, a co=\r\nmplete withdrawal of lower nature of man - lust, anger, jealousy, greed, co=\r\nvetousness - an abiding peace, calm, detachment, mental-illumination, genui=\r\nne compassion, a widening of the consciousness. Such an individual, even if=\r\n he/she just sits\n down next to another person, will exude a silent strong =\r\npeace and unselfish love which will automatically calm the minds and distur=\r\nbed emotions of lesser mortals ETC. THAT is the authentic, unhindered flow =\r\nof the Divine Power of any of the great deities. This comes even if one dei=\r\nty is properly realized in the causal planes of existence. But the astral f=\r\normation of the same deity, which is created by the force of our own pranas=\r\nhakti or Kundalini as the case maybe, is often not capable of affecting thi=\r\ns kind of a total transformation in a sadhaka. That is why it is limited. I=\r\nt is not limited because it can&#39;t&nbsp; get me a better job or a nice pay h=\r\nike or cure some diseases or bring me fame or any such material benefit if =\r\nI so ask of it - the astral formations of the deities can very easily do al=\r\nl these things in the physical world - but it is limited because it cannot =\r\nby itself give you the must authentic and persistent spirituality of the hi=\r\ngher\n planes, the one aim and destination of all genuine sadhana.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Si=\r\nnce this astral plane is the way it is, therefore it&#39;s extremely important =\r\nto keep actively working on ourselves to increase detachment, objectivity, =\r\ngenuine internal surrender (when that happens one accepts all life-situatio=\r\nns without the slightest grudge), humility, control of anger, lust, jealous=\r\ny etc. (all that is universally accepted as spiritual qualities). For unles=\r\ns these changes are affected at least to some degree in the mind and emotio=\r\nns of the sadhaka, one is simply not ready to reach the higher planes of Go=\r\nd and benefit from them spiritually. Moreover, at every stage of spiritual =\r\nevolution there is a gap between experience and realization. Only repeated =\r\nexperiences *may* lead to realization. One off experiences create a force n=\r\no doubt, but in time it fritters away, or worst, gets distorted by the impu=\r\nrities and conditioning of the sadhaka.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;&lt;&lt;span&gt;I am sure\n thi=\r\ns is not your \ntheory. You have taken it from yogi Aurobindo. Many times wh=\r\nen certain \nperson reach a stage in their spiritual path, others think what=\r\never this\n guy is uttering is&nbsp;complete truth, when in fact it is&nbsp;=\r\nfar from truth. \nOnce&nbsp;I saw in a article that Aurobindo said that Divi=\r\nne Lord who spoke \nGita completely forgot it after few minutes or so. I cou=\r\nld not believe \nwhat I was reading. Then my respect for this yogi went down=\r\n the drain.&gt;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;You surety is incorrect. There were certain even=\r\nts which happened in the last one and half years which made me sit down and=\r\n rethink my own understanding of spirituality. At about the same time I sta=\r\nrted worshiping a specific personality of the Divine Mother, and the more I=\r\n meditated on Her, the more would thoughts pour into my mind that my unders=\r\ntanding of spirituality is imperfect and has serious flaws. I tried, using =\r\nmy own meditations to find out what was wrong or rather imperfectly underst=\r\nood, what needed rethinking. First question I asked myself was, what is the=\r\n aim of spirituality? My mind could grasp some outlines of certain answers =\r\nand processes and truths. But it was still not exceptionally clear. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br=\r\n&gt;I had first read Sri Aurobindo when I was in college. I could not go beyon=\r\nd the first two pages. They were bouncers going one mile over my head. Thre=\r\ne years\n ago someone gave me a book of Sri Aurobindo. I could understand sa=\r\ny 10 percent, and rest I rejected, partly due to ignorance and partly due t=\r\no egoistic arrogance. Never opened any of his writing since then. This year=\r\n, as my sadhana was going on and as I was instinctively trying to correct t=\r\nhe flaws in my understanding, one day while meditating I had an inner thoug=\r\nht in the form of an image, which told me that I should start reading Sri A=\r\nurobindo but in a very specific manner. The image was very clear in my inne=\r\nr-eye, and thoroughly pressing on my consciousness. I opened his book again=\r\n, and read it in the prescribed manner and this time it made a LOT of sense=\r\n to me. What I was struggling to understand all this year, whose outline I =\r\ncould grasp yet not get a proper hang of, I was able to understand from his=\r\n writings with much deeper clarity.&nbsp; Many of my own experiences made m=\r\nore sense to me. Many sentences of Aghora books too made amply sense in a\n =\r\nnew light. I read 40 - 45 % of his writings. Then something in me told me t=\r\no stop at a certain point of his writings, for digesting the rest of the 60=\r\n % I will have to first make more spiritual progress. Otherwise the rationa=\r\nl mind will distort the information. So I stopped. He whom I had rejected f=\r\nirmly 3 years ago, now came back to sit on my consciousness like a blazing =\r\nsun. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The line that you mention, is from one of the earlier writings=\r\n of Sri Aurobindo on the historical problem of the Mahabharta. In the Mahab=\r\nharata, there is an incident which comes later on, after the great war and =\r\nwhen Yudhisthira was ruling the kingdom happily, when Arjuna asks Sri Krish=\r\nna to repeat the words he had spoken at the beginning of the war (The Gita)=\r\n once more since he has forgotten them, and Sri Krishna says, the time has =\r\npassed away (it was a special time when the Gita was spoken), he cannot rep=\r\neat the &quot;exact words&quot; once again. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Sri Krishna was the main\n Guru of=\r\n Aurobindo. Even Swami Vivekananda was one of his Gurus, for during the tim=\r\ne when Sri Aurobindo was in jail, for 15 days Swami Vivekananda would appea=\r\nr before him daily and instruct him on the various layers of the mind, whic=\r\nh he was not aware of till then. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;Swam=\r\ni Vivekananda had already left his physical body by then.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; It =\r\nwas in the writings of Sri Aurobindo that he mentioned about the left and r=\r\night hemisphere of the brain and their difference in functionality, and the=\r\nir connection to spirituality, about 30 years before medical science confir=\r\nmed the same. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt; Right from getting out of jail, to settling in Pondi=\r\ncherry, to pushing his own spiritual experiences further into states of Sah=\r\naja (which he describes in different terminology), etc etc, he was guided c=\r\nontinuously by the Adesha of Sri Krishna. He would literally hear the voice=\r\n of Krishna speaking to him, instructing him to do this or\n do that. Krishn=\r\na was his Guru, the Divine Mother beyond all manifestation, was his destina=\r\ntion. Anyway, my point is not to try and sell Sri Aurobindo&#39;s perspective o=\r\nf spirituality. I have benefited from it, but not necessary that everyone e=\r\nlse will also benefit. There are so many sadgurus who have come to India, e=\r\nach with their unique perspectives and ideas and philosophies. Each must in=\r\ndividually try and find whose ideas gel properly with our mental and emotio=\r\nnal makeup, and help us to progress on the path. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Though I now have =\r\na very deep respect for Sri Aurobindo, I maintain a safe distance from both=\r\n his critics and his blind-admirers. Both of them, in my opinion, have misu=\r\nnderstood the depth of his teachings. Both their love and their hatred is a=\r\n function of their own egos, like it was mine 3 years ago, and not based on=\r\n any genuine understanding or appreciation. In spirituality, no Sadguru can=\r\n be understood accurately or even slightly without\n sincere sadhana.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/s=\r\npan&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;div style=3D&quot;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-size: 1=\r\n6px; background-color: transparent; font-style: normal;&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;&lt;\nDis=\r\nclaimer---- My thinking is \nvery different due to Darshan and&nbsp;Grace of=\r\n Divine Mother &amp; Divine \nLord. Nobody should feel unhappy If I do not a=\r\ngree or follow the \nleader.Thanks.&gt;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I at-least will never fee=\r\nl unhappy if you disagree. There are \nmany saints, many philosophies, many =\r\npaths, not everyone is bound to \nlike every path.&nbsp; Disagreement is per=\r\nfectly ok. Because someone \ndisagrees with me or those whom I agree with, d=\r\noes not mean I like him \nany less. I try to keep my&nbsp; emotional side (w=\r\nhere respect, love, \ndislike, hatred, anger, passions exist) separate from =\r\nmy thinking mind. \nIt is very much possible, through practice, for a man to=\r\n disassociate \nhis rational-mind from the emotional-mind. So have no fears =\r\nthat your \ndisagreement is going to make me like you any less or any more.&lt;=\r\n/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=3D&quot;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-size: 16px; background-=\r\ncolor: transparent; font-style: normal; font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-s=\r\nerif;&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=3D&quot;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-size:=\r\n 16px; background-color: transparent; font-style: normal; font-family: aria=\r\nl,helvetica,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;The problem with the emotional part of our b=\r\neing is that it jumps up at appearances, running ahead to grasp the truth r=\r\nather than waiting patiently for the truth to arrive in all its aspects and=\r\n dimensions, and in the process it distorts the truth and then reacts to th=\r\nat distorted image. For example, recently in some social forums I posted a =\r\ncomment that I found the Tantrik Adwaitha far more appealing than Sri Adi S=\r\nhankara&#39;s Adwaitha, though the Adwaitha of Adi Shankara has many hard-selli=\r\nng supporters. Immediately some friends of mine on Twitter and otherwise, j=\r\numped to\n the false conclusion that I have disrespected Adi Shankara, and t=\r\nried best to make me &quot;see the truth&quot; by such grandiose statements that&nbsp=\r\n; Shankara is the &#39;final word&#39; on Adwaitha and everything else must be nece=\r\nssarily lesser. Or that I was making an egoistic denouncement. Both of whic=\r\nh are million light-years away from the truth. That Sri Adi Shankara was a =\r\nspecial Vibhuti (manifestation) of God, that much I am certain. His composi=\r\ntions are so brilliant that it can&#39;t be sufficiently appreciated in words. =\r\nYet, I have equally no qualms in rejecting his philosophy. And because I am=\r\n not bound to accept his philosophy, does not mean I respect or love him an=\r\ny less than any other great saint.&nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=3D&quot;color: r=\r\ngb(0, 0, 0); font-size: 16px; background-color: transparent; font-style: no=\r\nrmal; font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div=\r\n style=3D&quot;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-size: 16px; background-color: transpare=\r\nnt;\n font-style: normal; font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;If=\r\n you disrespect a man, and specially a saint, and then start disliking him =\r\ntoo with a passion, you are creating strong negative karmas. But if you can=\r\n disagree with someone without losing respect or love for the person, in an=\r\n objective manner, you reap very little karmic effects. That is why Lord Kr=\r\nishna too advices us to become more detached in life.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div styl=\r\ne=3D&quot;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-size: 16px; background-color: transparent; f=\r\nont-style: normal; font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/sp=\r\nan&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=3D&quot;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-size: 16px; background-col=\r\nor: transparent; font-style: normal; font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-seri=\r\nf;&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;In conclusion, Narasimha is totally correct. Many things cannot b=\r\ne sufficiently expressed in words without causing some distortion.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/=\r\ndiv&gt;&lt;div style=3D&quot;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-size: 16px; background-color:\n =\r\ntransparent; font-style: normal; font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;=\r\n&lt;br&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=3D&quot;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-size: 16px; =\r\nbackground-color: transparent; font-style: normal; font-family: arial,helve=\r\ntica,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;-Regards&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=3D&quot;color: rgb(0, 0,=\r\n 0); font-size: 16px; background-color: transparent; font-style: normal; fo=\r\nnt-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&nbsp;Rajarshi&lt;br&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/di=\r\nv&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;=\r\nb&gt;&lt;div class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;span class=3D&quot;Apple-style-span&quot; style=3D&quot;fon=\r\nt-size:16px;&quot;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;span class=3D&quot;Apple-style-span&quot; style=3D&quot;color:rgb(153, 1=\r\n53, 153);&quot;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;span class=3D&quot;yui_3_2_0_2_134243527249950=\r\n&quot; style=3D&quot;font-family:times new roman, new york, times, serif;&quot;&gt;awaktam wy=\r\naktimApannam manyantE mAmabuddhayah |&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt